text.text: My wife came to the restaurant for the first time. We are big seafood lovers. We ordered a cheese platter, clams on the half shell, seafood salad, and Scungilli over linguine in a red hot sauce. We shared everything. Everything was delicious. My wife felt that the clams were not fresh, but I disagreed with her. I thought the portion was a little small for the prices, but everything now a days cost a lot. The wine selection was adequate,  per glass, and bottle prices were a little high. The menu was huge a lot of choices. The dessert was very good, and Cappachino was so-so. Was surprised to see they did NOT charge you extra for using a credit card. That surprised me. Because every other restaurant does. I would definitely come back and other seafood items. Service was perfect, location perfect. No wait.

text.text:
Fina's Farmhouse shines with its Cobb Salad—crisp romaine, avocado, bacon, and tangy blue cheese dressing make it a fresh, satisfying lunch choice. For breakfast, the Steak Benny (tender steak topped with a runny poached egg and hollandaise) is rich and savory, while the Breakfast Board (eggs, meats, pancakes, and biscuits) offers a shareable feast with homestyle charm.

The cozy farmhouse vibe and attentive service elevate every meal. A must-visit for those craving quality ingredients and generous portions in Staten Island!

text.text:
I recently visited Fina’s Farmhouse in Staten Island for breakfast with my family and had a delightful experience.

Food:
•	Stuffed French Toast: This dish was exceptional—savory and flavorful, making for a satisfying start to the day.
•	Traditional Belgian Waffle: While the waffle was well-prepared, it was standard and didn’t stand out compared to the other dishes.
•	Eggs Benedict with Hash Browns and Bacon: This was a highlight. The eggs were perfectly poached, and the accompanying hash browns and bacon were cooked to perfection, enhancing the overall enjoyment of the meal.

Beverages:
•	The coffee was outstanding, complementing the breakfast dishes wonderfully.

Ambiance and Service:
•	The restaurant offers a cozy and welcoming atmosphere, ideal for a family breakfast.
•	The staff was friendly and attentive, contributing positively to our dining experience.

Overall, Fina’s Farmhouse provided a memorable breakfast experience with standout dishes like the Stuffed French Toast and Eggs Benedict. I highly recommend it for anyone seeking a quality breakfast spot in Staten Island.

I came here to celebrate my birthday and I absolutely love this restaurant. Everything is all homemade and is very delicious.

My family and I started out with having calmaria,  homemade meatballs, and rice ball.  All very delicious and homemade.  I wish they made the meatballs an entreee it was very, very delicious.

Then for the entrees I asked if they can make me chicken Francesca I got it with vegetables and potatoes it was very delicious.  I would highly recommend getting this dish even though it is not listed on their menu.  My husband and my father got their steak wow it was very delicious and it was actually medium well.  Next time I may get that dish.  My mother got a pasta dish with vegetables.  Everything was overall very delicious and a lot of left overs.

For dessert they came out and sang happy birthday to me and I decided to also get the Gelato it must had been the best Gelato ever.

I highly recommend coming here and supporting small businesses.

text.text:
I recently had the misfortune of ordering pizza from a local pizzeria that has left me—and my family—feeling utterly nauseous. This was not just any pizza; it was arguably the worst I’ve ever encountered in my life. The sauce tasted stale, and there were parts of the pizza that were missing cheese, as if they had simply forgotten to add it. To make matters worse, when I opened the box, it smelled more like a toxic cleaning product than the delicious aroma of fresh pizza. It felt like I was opening a box that had been fumigated rather than a beloved takeout meal. I’m genuinely trying to wrap my head around how a place that I’ve trusted could serve something so appalling.

What’s more disheartening is the response I received when I called to express my concerns. The owner was anything but friendly, insisting that this is how they always make their pizza. If that were true, I wouldn’t have ordered from them again after my first experience. Instead of taking responsibility or attempting to make amends, I was met with indifference. No offer of a replacement pizza, no refund—nothing. It’s as if they couldn’t care less about the quality of their food or the satisfaction of their customers. I’ve been a loyal patron, but this experience has shattered that trust completely.

After this encounter, I can confidently say I will never order from them again. It’s disappointing to think that a place I once enjoyed has fallen so far short of acceptable standards. My hope is that I—and my family—can recover from this horrible experience and find a better pizzeria that values quality and customer service. It’s truly unfortunate when a local business fails to uphold the basic tenets of good food and hospitality.

text.text: What started as a random walk-in when we first moved to Tottenville to chat about our cars with the owners and chatting for an hour without even knowing each other turned into a neighborhood staple for us. An amazing family owned restaurant with the kindest owners and the best food!! My family and I always order from them, our favorite local spot and we are so thankful for their kindness that they not only show to us but for the kindness that Victor shows to my two pups who mean the world to me. Our pups will occasionally walk us to Towne Deli, knowing that Victor will come outside and greet them with a smile on his face and cheese in his hand, the warmth and kindness is unmatched and does not go unnoticed. We are so happy to support a family owned small business as everyone should and will continue to do so! Thank you to Victor and his family for your dedication to bringing great food & connection to our community :)

I was super excited to come here, but this was disappointing to say the least. The pizza is not good. It almost tasted ”pre-made” - the cheese wasn’t very good, the overall vibe felt more like frozen pizza. A bit stingy on the pepperoni too. For a place that calls itself a pizza bar, you must have good pizza - Rocky’s misses the mark.

The highlight of the meal were the mozzarella sticks - they were good. Nonna’s sliders also really good, but it didn’t matter, because the pizza was so bad.

The service was good, but the ambiance in this place was lame. 1950’s music, boring vibe. Supposed to be a pizza bar, felt more like a traditional Italian restaurant that lacked identity.

Will not return. I wish I felt differently!

I would go back there in a heartbeat.

text.text:
I was born, grew up and attended grammar school at St. Thomas Aquinas in South Brooklyn - now part of Park Slope as of the 1970’s.
I moved to Los Angeles in 1980 for work, but I always come back to NY regularly to visit family and friends for all kinds of occasions.

One such time was in the summer of 2022 when my sister and I took six friends and their wives to dinner at Angelina’s Ristorante. I had never been there before, but all of my family and friends highly recommended Angelina’s and I am so glad that they did. We had a wonderful evening. The food was excellent and the service was exceptional.

So, when I decided to put a reunion together for my St. Thomas Aquinas classmates on September 14, 2024, I suggested that we have it at Angelina’s.

Some of my classmates live in Staten Island and were very happy that we choose Angelina’s.  The rest of us came in from Colorado, Chicago, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Long Island, Westchester County, Brooklyn and Los Angeles.

All and all there were twenty of us.  We had a wonderful evening and we all agreed that we will be doing it again next year at Angelina’s

This is a very special thank you to everyone who made our evening a Night to Remember.

Thank you Angelina, Brandi, Josephine, Felix, Ida, Damiano, Jairo and Richy.

Looking forward to seeing all of you next year.

Sincerely,
John Rizzo & The STA Class of 1963
